Kiess does not control the GNF, cannot bypass it, and must use it anyway. The Trade Syndics update a standing file each season from convoy marshal reports.
Kiess respects the Northern Covenant because it works: caravans move, tithes are predictable, neither city garrisons the interior. But marshals report erosion: unlit lamp-posts, cracked waystones, Ashfang warbands growing bolder in the Ironpine Rise where Midgaard patrols thin.
The Passage Tithe (grain, salt, oil, nails) is studied by Syndics as a risk-sharing model for Roc Road. It kept goods flowing during the Ash Winters where gold alone would have failed.
Kiess fears the Covenant's brittleness. It depends on Midgaard and Kowloon both maintaining commitments. If either city's attention drifts (as Midgaard's has at Sepulchur Pasture and the Eccentric Woodland), the Covenant becomes a sealed document governing an ungoverned road.
Roadwardens and lamp-keepers are reliable partners. Mire-clans trade fairly. Stone-antler circles are left alone; claiming jurisdiction over their megalith groves is the overreach that killed Evermeet.
Wall Command maintains no permanent forest presence. This is deliberate. Kiess extends influence through commerce, not garrison. Convoy marshals carry Syndic seals and emergency payment authority.
The Prism's lesson: Evermeet ignored its supply lines until they were cut. Kiess watches the forest because a trade city that loses sight of its arteries is already dying.

