The GNF is Kowloon's southern lifeline. Every overland export (silk, salt fish, phosphorescent dye) leaving the Tide Gate must pass through 400 miles of canopy. The Lantern Road is survival, not scenery.
The Courier Lantern Office considers the Bent Mile Principle (Ilren Voss's road-yielding doctrine) the oldest expression of civic lantern-keeping. Kowloon's signal network descends from the same tradition. Knot-signs on Lantern Road posts remain operationally readable by Kowloon Lampkeepers.
The Northern Covenant mirrors Kowloon's Neon Covenant: an agreement inked in the open, resistant to alteration in darkness. The Jade Magistracy trusts compacts that survive scrutiny.
The Ash Winters connect to Kowloon directly. The same Cinderteeth volcanic fallout that poisoned forest streams became Kowloon's Ashfall Monsoon. The Passage Tithe (grain, salt, lamp oil, iron nails) speaks Kowloon's economic language: material payment over anonymous coin.
Five zones south to north: Southern Verge (Midgaard's porch), Mosswater Bends (dreaded crossings), Ironpine Rise (swallows lantern light), Ancestor Deeps (luminescent moss the Courier Office calls "the forest's Neon Covenant"), Northern Crown (Kowloon's territory, patrolled by Wardens of Iron within half a day of the Jade Gate).
Ashfang warbands are marked crimson in the threat registry. Their ash-tooth decoration mocks the Ashfall Vigil by wearing catastrophe as fashion.
When Lantern Road lamps go dark, Kowloon's markets feel it within the week. Kowloon does not romanticize the forest. It counts on it.

