Rakuen views the GNF's Northern Covenant as proof of Midgaard's selective cooperation. The Ember Wardens teach recruits about it before the three refusals.
The Covenant demonstrates Midgaard understands shared governance: joint jurisdiction, mutual stewardship, passage tithes in grain and salt, shrine groves protected. The Lantern Road bends around sacred groves per the Bent Mile Principle. These mirror Rakuen's own principles from the Southward Compact, written by Elys Savan a generation before the Covenant.
Three times Rakuen petitioned for inclusion in a similar civic framework. Three times Midgaard refused, citing incompatible accounting, route instability, and constitutional grounds.
During the Ash Winters, Midgaard responded to forest devastation with the adaptive Passage Tithe. When the same ash poisoned Rakuen's cisterns and killed its orchards, Midgaard responded with silence. The Cracked Promise Stone on the northern trail reads: "They will share water with a waystone before they share it with a neighbor."
Every forest faction has a negotiated place in Midgaard's ledger: Roadwardens answer to the Joint Bureau, Mire-clans hold barter licenses, Stone-antler circles receive ritual writs. Rakuen has no place in that ledger.
The Garden Ledger Clerks keep a pressed lantern-flower from the Southern Verge beside their copy of the Southward Compact. The light Midgaard hangs for travelers, it will not hang for Rakuen. Rakuen tends its own lanterns.

