Mafdet classifies the GNF under Indirect Provenance, Class Two. Forest goods (timber, resin, medicinal bark, mire-clan fish oil) reach Mafdet's quays after two or three ownership changes along oasis corridors. The forest is distant but not irrelevant; it is difficult to attest.
The Lantern Road interests Harbor Wardens as an inland signal system analogous to Mafdet's own Tidemouth signal towers. When road lamps go dark, goods stop moving, the oasis corridor contracts, and Mafdet manifests thin.
The Passage Tithe (grain, salt, oil, iron nails) functions as an attestation system. Commodity payment carries implicit provenance: identifiable origin, identifiable hands. Mafdet's Ledger Houses can work with commodity tithe. Coin is anonymous. Commodity payment is self-documenting.
The Northern Covenant is the kind of sworn compact the Shrine of the First Claw understands. But it binds only Midgaard and Kowloon. Neither has sworn at Mafdet's shrine. Their compact is their business until it breaks. Broken compacts produce unattested cargo, displaced peoples, and supply disruption, which become Mafdet's problem.
Ashfang warbands are a provenance problem. Raider-seized goods carry no chain of custody. Forest-origin cargo with inconsistent seals is flagged by the Quarantine Ledger for secondary inspection. Mafdet does not moralize about banditry. It requires documentation. Unprovable origin means the goods do not leave port.
The forest feeds Mafdet at two removes. Mafdet watches it like a harbor watches upstream weather: not to control it, but to classify what arrives.
